title.narrative: Media for Transparent and Accountable Governance (M-TAG)

description.narrative: (Georgia): M-TAG works with competitively selected group of 14 media organizations throughout Georgia to concurrently increase their capacity in content production, web publishing, and business operations. M-TAG works with media partners to provide fact-based reporting and analysis, thus helping the audience to discern disinformation and propaganda and combat anti-Western sentiment M-TAG supports raising reporting standards across the journalism profession by providing operational funds to Ethics Charter and Multimedia Education Center (MEC), to acquire industry-relevant and hands-on production skills. M-TAG helps media partners keep ethnic minority communities and communities affected by conflict on both sides of Administrative Boundary Line informed and provides them with platforms for expression and exchange of ideas and information.With FY 2019 Funds the program will support regional outlets to disseminate COVID-19 related critical pandemic, social or political information in a timely manner. M-TAG will support regional media outlets, including those covering minority communities with language appropriate content, through content production grants and technical assistance to ensure information about continued vigilance, re-emergence and response and recovery efforts and opportunities is well communicated to Georgia's citizens. M-TAG will also support media outlets to analyze and report of COVID-19 response and recovery efforts and communicate citizen's concerns to decision makers at the local and central levels. M-TAG will continue to assist media outlets to improve their online presence, including website development, multimedia content production, online advertising, analytics, editorial management, and management of online TV studios. In addition, the program will continue to support the Georgian Charter of Journalistic Ethics and the Multimedia Education Center, two key institutions that promote high standards in Georgia's media sector.. .

title.narrative: Advancing CSO Capacities and Engaging Society for Sustainability (ACCESS)

description.narrative: (Georgia): .USAID's Advancing Civil Society Capacities and Engaging Society for Sustainability (ACCESS) activity works to increase citizen engagement with Georgian civil society organizations (CSOs) from across the democratic spectrum. The activity, improves organizational and technical capacity of CSOs to monitor and influence government policies and processes in a non-partisan manner. ACCESS achieves these outcomes through a combination of small grants, trainings, and technical assistance to local organizations; and by supporting the Network of Centers for Civic Engagement in 10 cities, which operate as politically neutral gathering spaces for public discourse on issues of relevant to the Georgian public. By enabling a more constituent-connected, organizationally mature cadre of CSOs, activities assist CSOs to become legitimate representatives of citizens' concerns.With FY 2019 funds ACCESS will expand COVID-19-related programming to address medium and longer-term implications of the pandemic. ACCESS will work with local organizations to continue to build communities' trust in civil society, demonstrate efficient use of resources and encourage community investment in COVID-19 related activities through volunteerism and community resource mobilization. The activity builds the capacity of the civil society sector to contribute to more transparent and accountable governance (ICS MO 1.1) by facilitating dialogue between citizens and their government about key priorities. This activity aligns with U.S. national security interests and supports the U.S. policy priority of promoting American leadership through balanced engagement and increased partnerships with civil society (JSP 3.3 and JRS 4.1). The activity works to counter Russian soft power that discredits civil society. It mitigates democratic backsliding by ensuring an active citizenry and supports the U.S. goals to advance Georgia's Euro-Atlantic integration... .. .. .

title.narrative: The Zrda Activity in Georgia (Zrda)

description.narrative: (Georgia): Russian occupation of Abkhazia and South Ossetia, borderization along these regions, and discontent in communities with ethnically or religiously marginalized populations are direct threats to Georgia's economic and political stability. By building economic resilience in communities along the administrative boundary line (ABL) and regions with marginalized populations, the Zrda program directly counters malign Kremlin influence, contributes to ongoing economic activity along the ABL, and supports Georgia to restore its territorial integrity...Zrda will build the economic resilience of more than 80 communities by supporting at least 800 micro-, small- and medium-sized enterprises (MSMEs) to acquire equipment and certifications to increase productive capacity and meet international quality standards for goods and services. Zrda will also support the GOG agencies to promote new technologies and innovation; strengthen the public and private sector extension systems; extend digital marketing and electronic matchmaking services between buyers, producers, and service providers; and develop public-private partnerships to build economic opportunities in targeted communities. In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, Zrda will support Georgia's hospitality businesses across 17 municipalities to implement required sanitary regulations...Zrda will provide $1.3 million in training, grants, and technical assistance to advance USAID/Georgia's CDCS DO1: Resilience to external malign influence strengthened (CAATSA Goal 8) and DO3: Inclusive high-value employment opportunities through increased economic growth. By co-investing with the private sector and the GOG to incentivize new business development along the ABL (JRS 2.3.1), Zrda ensures effectiveness to the American taxpayer (JSP 4), promotes American leadership through balanced engagement (JSP 3.3), and mobilizes additional resources to advance Georgia's self-reliance (JRS 5.2.1)... .. .

title.narrative: Good Governance Initiative (GGI)

description.narrative: (Georgia): .Good Governance Initiative (GGI) is designed to support the GOG in strengthening transparency, accountability, and effectiveness of select governance and service delivery systems to achieve: improved administrative and financial management of public institutions; improved access to independent, reliable and balanced information on government performance; strengthened policy development and lawmaking; and strengthened institutional oversight of GOG. GGI's government counterparts include the Prime Minister's Office; the Ministries of Finance, Health, Justice, and Regional Development; Parliament; the State Audit Office; Public Defender's and State Inspector's Offices and select local governments. Interventions will work with government and civil society representatives to enhance public participation, public awareness and monitoring of public administration and parliamentary strengthening reforms. The activity will have emphasis on COVID19 response. ..Using FY 2019 funds, GGI's activities will be focused on:.Supporting the GoG in COVID19 response through policy research in the governance areas impacted by the COVID-19 pandemic; analysis of government operations during the pandemic; mapping of public services and developing recommendations for operationalizing essential public services to be accessible remotely; developing guidelines for the operation of civil service during the crisis; supporting remote operations of the Parliament; etc. Supporting the implementation of the Local Government Decentralization Strategy (2020-2025) by providing necessary technical assistance in select areas.Supporting the implementation of Anti-Corruption Action Plan (2019-2020) and Open Government Partnership Action Plans in select municipalities.Improving state oversight through supporting the Parliament and the State Audit Office as well as building internal control functions of the government agencies... .

description.narrative: The HealthLink Project, Accelerating Ukraines Efforts to End HIV, has started in October 2017. title.narrative: Cultivating Media Independence (CMI) Initiative Activity in the Kyrgyz Republic, Media-K

description.narrative: (Kyrgyz Republic): USAID's Media-K initiative will continue to support the development of a more professional, financially viable, and independent media sector. This activity will result in media outlets which better serve the public interest by providing access to diverse and balanced information and analyses about the issues that are of most concern to citizens, while providing a counterweight to state-funded media. This activity will include the provision of training, technical expertise, and mentoring to Kyrgyzstani journalists, media outlets, and production companies to help them build their skills and increase the production of high-quality domestic content. The activity will stimulate the production of domestic content that responds to audience demand, strengthen the ability of targeted media outlets to use audience research to attract more advertising, and bring together disparate stakeholders to advocate for a healthy enabling environment for media businesses. This activity supports ICS objective 3.1: Support a more inclusive and accountable democracy.

Objectives for Kyrgyz Republic: Media-K aims to strengthen the professionalism and independence of media in the Kyrgyz Republic in order to ensure that citizens of the Kyrgyz Republic have greater access to diverse and balanced information, are less vulnerable to media bias, and are empowered to make better-informed civic decisions that reflect their communities’ priorities to best serve the public interest.

title.narrative: Afghanistan's Measure for Accountability and Transparency ( AMANAT)

description.narrative: (Afghanistan): With FY 2020 resources, USAID will continue to implement Afghanistan's Measure for Accountability and Transparency (AMANAT) activity. AMANAT aims to strengthen the Government of Afghanistan (GOA) institutions and civil society organizations (CSOs) to identify vulnerabilities to corruption in the delivery of public services, and develop activities to address these vulnerabilities...This program is designed to: 1) improve the performance, legitimacy, and technical capacity of the GoA to reduce and prevent corruption in government public services and functions; 2) support selected GoA institutions with technical assistance for procedural reforms based on recommendations identified in the vulnerabilities to corruption assessments; 3) strengthen local CSOs' capacity to test and monitor the effectiveness of those reforms and to advocate for their implementation where necessary; 4) train CSOs to perform watchdog functions to hold the government accountable to the public by analyzing anti-corruption shortcomings in legislation, conducting social auditing, and supporting citizen monitoring; and 5) support the Ministry of Public Health's current COVID-19 campaign through the dissemination of anti-corruption messaging in Kabul and seven provinces, through a 3-month (June 15 - September 15) Social Behavior Change Communication and Distance Learning Campaign..

Objectives for Afghanistan: Project objectives include: Support selected government institutions in facilitated self-assessments to identify corruption risks in their internal procedures. Strengthen internal audit functions in the selected government agencies. Work closely with central government agencies, use business process reengineering and other techniques to develop tailored corruption risk mitigation plans and support their implementation. Monitor implementation of these reforms over time to promote learning and adaptation. Mobilize civil society groups in Kabul and selected provinces to act as “government watchdogs” to address corruption. Enable CSOs to analyze shortcomings in legislation addressing corruption. Support CSO initiatives that increase public awareness, advocacy, monitoring and oversight activities through a grants program.

title.narrative: Assistance for the Development of Afghan Legal Access and Transparency (ADALAT)

description.narrative: (Afghanistan): ADALAT works with the formal and informal justice actors to ensure fair and transparent implementation of the rule of law for all Afghan citizens. ADALAT work's to increase effectiveness and reach of the formal justice sector; strengthen linkages between the formal & traditional justice sectors; and increase citizen demand for quality legal services by increasing citizens' legal awareness and creating clinical legal education programs. FY 2020 resources to build the technical capacity and improve administrative operations of the judiciary, train Afghan legal professionals, improve case management system, improve the informal justice sector decisions, train communities in traditional dispute resolution, and increase awareness among Afghan citizens of their rights under the law. ..FY 2020 resources to strengthen the informal justice system through the Justice Engagement Model implemented by CSO partners. Traditional dispute resolution participants in the informal justice system support community peace and harmony through trusted traditional approaches, thus preventing escalation of tensions as cases work their way through the formal justice system. To addres increase in GBV during the COVID-19 pandemic, ADALAT will implement activities to increase knowledge and awareness of GBV. ADALAT will address the negative impacts of impunity for perpetrators of GBV in both the formal and informal justice systems...ADALAT collaborates with the courts, Ministry of Justice (MOJ), civil society organizations, target universities, and traditional dispute resolution bodies to achieve these objectives. Improving rule of law is a cornerstone of security, democracy, and peace. ..This program also contributes to the USAID Mission's Integrated Country Strategy goal of supporting the Afghan government to become stable, democratic, and responsive to citizens by improving citizen access to justice..... .. ...

Objectives for Afghanistan: ADALAT’s (“justice” in Dari and Pashto) objective is to improve citizen access to justice. ADALAT increases efficiency and integrity in the formal justice system through training and the development of more robust court systems and procedures. At the same time, ADALAT works to create stronger links between the formal and informal justice sectors and greater consistency in the application of Afghan law by traditional dispute resolution actors.Finally, ADALAT seeks to satisfy citizen demand for quality legal services through expanded public legal education, improved legal education, and enhanced legal assistance.

title.narrative: Suaahara II (Integrated Nutrition Program II)

description.narrative: (Nepal): .Suahaara II focuses on the 1,000-day period between conception and a child's second birthday as a critical window to shape a child's cognitive and physical development through improved nutrition. With FY 2020 funds, the activity will continue to reduce the prevalence of stunting, underweight, and wasting among children; improve household health, nutrition and water, sanitation and hygiene behaviors and practices; increase the use of quality health services; increase the consumption of diverse and nutritious foods by women and their families; and support counseling and behavior change communication on family planning at mothers' groups. Suaahara II will work with the GON in 389 municipalities using evidence-based, multi-sectoral nutrition interventions at the policy, community, and household levels. Suaahara II will improve health and nutrition behaviors and reduce the impact of health emergencies such as COVID-19 on nutrition by strengthening community health systems. This will include training health facility staff on the promotion of exclusive breastfeeding, infant and young child feeding, maternal and newborn care, integrated management of acute malnutrition, integrated management of childhood illness, and maternal and adolescent nutrition. In addition, it will promote essential hygiene actions such as safe drinking water and disposal of feces, healthy timing and spacing for pregnancy, and will provide information on a wide range of voluntary family planning methods and information on service availability. ..Helen Keller International has vast experience implementing integrated nutrition interventions, which contribute to Nepal's self-reliance. Improving nutritional health ensures a healthy and productive workforce in support of Embassy Kathmandu's ICS Goal Two: Increase America's prosperity by developing Nepal as a reliable economic partner, and MO 2.2, Nepal improves health and education outcomes to increase economic productivity....

Objectives for Nepal: Promote key Maternal, Infant and Young Child Nutrition (MIYCN) practices through an intensivebehavior change strategy, including interpersonal communication activities, radio programs, and theuse of mobile technology at the community level. Expand coverage of the community-based integrated management of newborn and childhood illnessprogram and strengthen growth monitoring and promotion at outreach clinics and health facilities. Enhance clean water, sanitation, and hygiene conditions of household facilities and establish privatesector linkages to promote WASH technologies. Improve consumption of nutritious food through increased production, improved post-harveststorage, and processing diverse nutritious food, especially for women farmers from disadvantagedgroups. Strengthen coordination on health and nutrition between government and other stakeholdersthrough the Food Security and Nutrition Coordination Committee, Nepal Nutrition Group,Nutrition Technical Committee, Safe Motherhood sub- committee, Family Planning Sub -committee,and Reproductive Health Coordination Committee. Strengthen the technical, managerial, operational capacity of health and non-health sectorstakeholders at the district and Village Development Committee (VDC) levels to enhance MSNPimplementation.

description.narrative: (Nepal): The Civil Society: Mutual Accountability Project (CS:MAP) supports civil society organizations (CSOs), non-profit organizations, non-government media, and member-based organizations to foster a more legitimate, accountable, and resilient Nepali civil society to advance citizen demands. FY 2020 resources will build the capacity of key institutions to develop governance standards that adhere to international norms; foster engagement with the GON to help enact and implement policies that meet public demands; provide training on data-driven research and advocacy; and promote social accountability, crisis response mechanisms, information, and communication technology tools. CS:MAP also supports the GON's human rights oversight institutions to enhance accountability on human rights issues and train human right defenders. COVID-19 interventions will focus on citizen advocacy, countering disinformation, and engagement with the government to improve service delivery..FHI 360 has worked for over two decades in Nepal to improve public awareness, promote the use of social accountability, and advance the institutional sustainability of CSOs and the media. NS is critical to achieving U.S. objectives in the Integrated Country Strategy (ICS) and the Indo-Pacific Strategy. CS:MAP supports Embassy Kathmandu's ICS Mission Goal One: Promote American Security by supporting a stable, secure, democratic, and sovereign Nepal and Mission Objective 1.3, Nepal successfully transitions to a more stable, inclusive, and effective federal democracy based on international norms and free from malign influence. .

Objectives for Nepal: The project aims to establish a favorable environment in which Nepali civil society and media operates; Enhance the capacity of Nepali CSOs and media to collaboratively and constructively engage in policy advocacy. Enhance coordination and effective civil society and media oversight of public resource use and service delivery. Strengthen organizational capacity and sustainability of CSO and media working in USAID priority sectors.

description.narrative: (Bangladesh): .The Rice and Diversified Crops activity will partner with private sector firms and other stakeholders to improve rice productivity by smallholder farmers, as well as enable them to acquire the skills and knowledge for enhanced rotational crops that will strengthen market competitiveness in the agriculture sector by improving value chain efficiencies, access to finance, and post-harvest services. The activity will help strengthen input and seed systems, and incentivize crop diversification with rotational crops, such as value-added rice varieties, lentils, mustard, mung beans, and sunflowers, thereby increasing export volume and enabling higher returns to local firms and smallholder farmers. It will work with local market actors to generate business opportunities for US firms to collaborate with Bangladeshi companies and explore domestic market opportunities. The activity will provide training and resources that will build capacity of input suppliers to develop innovative marketing strategies so as to develop a loyal customer base. It will also build the capacity of supporting market actors, including financial service providers and business development service providers, with improved services and business models. To contribute to reducing the impact of COVID-19, the activity will strengthen or re-establish local markets by investing in key value chains; support mechanization and labor saving methods, due to potential labor shortages; identify other opportunities to increase the financial resilience of small and medium enterprises; and leverage existing information dissemination programs (e.g., extension and digital tools) to share critical COVID-19 messages...This activity will support the Global Food Security Strategy and significantly contribute to achieving the State-USAID Joint Strategic Plan Goal Two, the Indo-Pacific Strategy through private sector engagement, and U.S. government's mission objective of improved food security in Bangladesh

title.narrative: Social and Behavior Change Communication Activity (Ujjiban)

description.narrative: (Bangladesh): The Ujjiban Social and Behavior Change Communication (SBCC) activity will generate demand for and increase the use of high-quality services for maternal, neonatal, child and adolescent health; family planning; nutrition and tuberculosis, and improve adoption of healthy behaviors in selected districts under in both Sylhet and Chattrogram divisions. At the national level, Ujjiban will strengthen the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare's capacity and systems, to effectively design, develop, coordinate and implement SBCC interventions. With FY 2020 funds, Ujjiban will intensify its focus on gender and health by using diverse communication media and methods (both traditional and new) as well as community outreach programs to encourage audience members to adopt key health behaviors in the areas of maternal, neonatal and child health; family planning, tuberculosis, and nutrition. Ujjiban will also carry out campaigns to raise awareness on ending early marriage and combating gender-based violence. The activity will further explore opportunities to leverage the private sector to ensure greater coverage of Ujjiban's SBCC products. To address risk communication and community engagement on COVID-19, USAID, through the Ujjiban activity, will strengthen risk communication systems, improve public communication, support community engagement, and address misperceptions and misinformation.This activity will support the U.S. National Security Strategy Pillar IV, the State-USAID Joint Strategic Plan Goal Two, and the U.S. government's mission objective of improved health status in Bangladesh..

title.narrative: FTF Bangladesh USAID’s Leaving No One Behind Activity

description.narrative: (Bangladesh): Mission Aviation Fellowship (MAF) flight will continue supporting USAID and its partner agencies to access hard-to-reach areas in Bangladesh to ensure that when development goals are achieved, they are achieved for everyone. Through chartered and shuttle flights, MAF will continue and broaden its flight services to all development and humanitarian agencies working to save human life and improve the livelihoods of vulnerable people in Bangladesh. MAF flight services will help increase the chances of aid agencies accessing hard-to-reach-areas towards ensuring that no one was left behind. This activity enables improved access to remote and marginalized areas, which is necessary for effective activity oversight and accountability. This activity was selected as the most cost effective way to provide activity oversight in remote areas for humanitarian assistance. MAF will contribute to activity monitoring oversight, needs assessment, joint missions with other development partners and private sector organizations in the Chittagong Hill Tracts, Rohingya and host communities, as well as the areas focused on health, education, and population. The service will be used where the commercial vehicles are not feasible and less accessible. In addition MAF service may contribute to emergency services for medical supply for COVID test kits, lab reagents and TOT for service providers in remote public health facilities. The activity will support the U.S. National Security Strategy Pillar IV, the State-USAID Joint Strategic Plan Goal Two, and the U.S. government's mission objective of improved health status in Bangladesh.. .

title.narrative: Chittagong Hill Tracts Watershed Co-Management Activity (CHTWCA)

description.narrative: (Bangladesh): CHTWCA builds regional resilience by reducing threats to ecosystems and wildlife through improved governance of natural resources. Its biodiversity objective is to reduce threats through an integrated ecosystem management approach that conserves the natural habitats of Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) watershed through environmental governance mechanisms. With FY 2020 funds, CHTWCA will provide direct technical assistance to the Forest Department, Ministry of CHT Affairs, Hill District Councils, Village Common Forest Management Committees and forest dependent communities to strengthen gender responsive local resilience by sustaining capacity to protect and manage the natural ecosystems of the CHT. This approach will improve the management of community and government managed forests that contributes to an integrated ecosystem management process. It will focus on finalizing an integrated watershed management plan for Reserved Forests. It will provide training on sustainable forest management, market linked resilient livelihoods and livelihood diversification. During COVID-19, UNDP will help communities to continue resilient livelihoods with market and private sector linkages. It will also raise awareness against poaching and illegal logging to ensure these activities do not increase during this period.UNDP is one of the few actors active in CHT, and has an unique comparative advantage due to its long experience, technical expertise, and established working relationships with local and government stakeholders. A community-based approach including co-management in the protected areas is the best approach through CHTWCA because it brings a diverse set of community members together for decisions to protect forest areas for water security.CHTWCA aligns with U.S. National Security Objectives of countering illegal trafficking in drugs, persons, and wildlife, and supports the U.S. government's objective of strengthening resilience to natural hazards..

title.narrative: USAID Inform Asia Associate Award #2 - Technical assistance to strengthen malaria surveillance and the use of strategic information for malaria programming

description.narrative: (USAID Regional Development Mission-Asia (RDM/A)): .This activity provides technical assistance to the Thai national malaria program to: 1) strengthen malaria surveillance systems for the detection, notification, and response to malaria cases; 2) evaluate malaria elimination approaches and strategies for implementation and scale-up; and 3) generate and use strategic information (including data from anti-malarial drug therapeutic efficacy monitoring and documentation write-ups). Technical assistance provided through Inform Asia will result in the development of key strategic information products used by various key stakeholders, such as a user-friendly malaria information system, dashboards to facilitate analysis and decision-making, technical assessments, advocacy briefs, and relevant publications. USAID expects that by the end of this award, Thailand's national malaria program will have increased technical capacity to use strategic information to plan, budget, implement, and monitor data-driven, technically sound, and cost-effective malaria programming that maximizes disease impact-a cornerstone in the road to a malaria-free Thailand by 2024. Strengthening malaria elimination is within the interest of global and US national security since it helps to create a more stable and prosperous region that advances American security and economic interests. Furthermore, successful health programs are a key component to ensuring and enhancing prosperity and good governance. For FY 2020, the activity will focus on the dashboard and visualization of the drug resistance monitoring data system, or iDES, integration of new essential data sets, providing online training on surveillance for elimination efforts adapted to COVID-19, providing M&E and data analysis for malaria elimination, and building government staff capacity on MIS data use for research and malaria elimination studies. .. .

title.narrative: USAID: Thailand CTIP

description.narrative: (Thailand): .As noted in the 2020 U.S. Trafficking in Persons Report, Thailand continues to be a key destination and transit point for human trafficking. USAID Thailand's Countering Trafficking in Persons (CTIP) activity employs a survivor-centered, gender-responsive approach to reduce vulnerability to trafficking and to protect the rights of trafficked persons. The activity works in the construction, agriculture, and fishing and seafood processing sectors across six provinces in Thailand. It reduces demand and use of exploitative labor by incentivizing businesses and employers to improve worker recruitment, worker welfare, and grievance systems, while providing technical assistance to the Royal Thai Government and local civil society organizations (CSOs) to strengthen their protection systems. The activity supports CSOs and migrant worker networks in increasing the awareness of at-risk populations of their rights and improving the attitudes of the Thai public toward migrant workers using a social behavioral change communication approach. At-risk migrant workers and trafficked persons further receive help with livelihood opportunities from CSOs as they reintegrate into their communities. Thailand CTIP engages U.S. buyers and companies with supply chains in Thailand to promote and protect labor rights and interests against exploitative practices that promote transnational criminal networks and destabilize the region. This activity supports the Presidential Executive Order on Enforcing Federal Law with Respect to Transnational Criminal Organizations and Preventing International Trafficking. With the emergence of the global COVID-19 pandemic, Thailand CTIP will adapt activities by adding newly developed communications materials that will include health-related information and tips to help migrants safeguard their rights and mental health in languages they can understand (i.e., Burmese, Khmer, Lao)..

title.narrative: USAID Laos CTIP

description.narrative: (Laos): .USAID Laos Counter Trafficking In Persons (CTIP) is a five-year activity that works to reduce vulnerability to human trafficking among targeted populations in Laos by supporting vocational training and employment opportunities for vulnerable populations, including trafficking survivors who are at risk for re-trafficking. Laos is a source - and to a lesser extent, a transit and destination country - for women, children and men subjected to sex trafficking and forced labor. Victims are often migrants seeking opportunities abroad who then experience labor or sexual exploitation in destination countries, most often Thailand, but also including Vietnam, Malaysia, and China...USAID Laos CTIP showcases a model of prevention and protection for the Lao government and other partners to learn from, support, and sustain as it strives to combat human trafficking. This approach exemplifies the idea of the Journey to Self-Reliance by working with Lao counterparts to build their capacity and commitment to manage CTIP interventions on their own in the future. It also supports USAID's vision for advancing America's Indo-Pacific vision by centering victims and at-risk populations, reflecting a human rights based approach consistent with the Indo-Pacific Transparency Initiative (IPTI), which was launched by Vice President Pence in November 2018. USAID Laos CTIP represents a key component of the agency's commitment to the human rights dimension of IPTI in Laos...The activity seeks to sustain progress on combating TIP: Laos rose to the Tier 2 Watchlist in the State Department's 2019 Trafficking in Persons report, up from Tier 3 in 2018. To maintain that momentum and avoid backsliding, interventions include assistance with implementing national laws, policies, and programs, as well as the provision of high-quality support services and better economic and employment opportunities to trafficked persons. Continued support on CTIP is a top Embassy priority..

title.narrative: Strengthening Urban Resilience for Growth with Equity (SURGE)

description.narrative: (Philippines): The SURGE activity is a crucial component of USAID/Philippines' Cities Development Initiative, which promotes more balanced and resilient urban growth, reduced economic disparities, and improved socio-economic conditions for secondary cities and surrounding rural areas, helping develop economic growth hubs outside of Metro Manila and Cebu. SURGE will continue to promote local economic development and expand urban-rural connectivity and access. The activity reinforces USAID goals and policies by helping local governments advance on their paths to self-reliance.To boost partner cities' ability to generate their own resources, SURGE will improve asset and public financial management. It will promote greater transparency, accountability, and effectiveness in local financial planning, revenue generation, and budgeting. The activity will help streamline and automate business permitting processes to reduce red tape and costs to local enterprises, and strengthen the capacity of local economic and investment promotion offices. The activity will bolster land tenure security by improving land information systems and land adjudication processes. It will also improve land use and development planning by integrating vulnerability assessments and disaster preparedness measures. SURGE will support inter-municipal cooperation and metropolitan arrangements that improve coordination between the prime city and adjacent municipalities. It will support public and private participation in regional development planning and improve national-municipal coordination, with particular focus on infrastructure development. The activity will support local government initiatives on economic development and job generation in such sectors as agribusiness and tourism development. This enables partner cities to participate as hubs for greater trade and investment. The activity will also support measures to improve the delivery of public services, such as traffic management.. .. .

Objectives for Philippines: Improve urban development and planning. Promote low-emission local economic development. Facilitate greater connectivity and access between urban and rural areas. Promote social inclusion

title.narrative: Fish Right

description.narrative: (Philippines): .USAID and a consortium of universities and non-government organizations support the Bureau of Fisheries and Aquatic Resources (BFAR) and other stakeholders in applying ecosystem-based fisheries management (EBFM) in 48 municipalities across three marine key biodiversity areas (MKBAs) in the Philippines. The consortium advances EBFM skills of fisheries officers from BFAR and local government units to set up management boards, facilitate planning, and establish harvest control measures (HCMs) for ecologically important fish stocks. HCMs ensure the effective implementation of fisheries catch limits, seasonal closures, and marine protected area (MPA) networks. The activity supports resilient MPA network designs to maximize ecological connectivity between areas and further protect marine resources. Facilitating participatory consensus building processes help broaden stakeholder reach and equitably negotiate the HCMs. In the Visayan Sea, USAID will support a management plan that will reduce over fishing of blue swimming crabs and protect their ecological habitats. USAID will address illegal, unreported and unregulated (IUU) fishing by developing an IUU fishing index and monitoring dashboards, improving policies to prevent illegal trade, and supporting social behavior change campaigns. USAID will also use remote sensing and other tools to restore mangroves, support community livelihoods, and promote gender equity through concession agreements to women's associations for mangrove management, while reducing greenhouse gas emissions. USAID will support spatial distribution analyses to better understand the ecological interdependence of marine systems in Palawan and the West Philippine Sea, a priority seascape under the Coral Triangle Initiative. USAID will further partner with the private sector to accelerate value chain recovery from COVID-19, while setting in place the biodiversity safeguards in all parts of the value chains. .. ...... .

title.narrative: Health Technical Assistance Project (BANTU)

description.narrative: (Indonesia): The Bantu project will provide specialized, high-level technical assistance to USAID, USAID-funded programs, the Government of Indonesia (GOI) (e.g. Ministry of Health), parastatal organizations (e.g., Eijkman Institute), sub-national government (e.g., district health office), non-governmental organizations (NGOs), civil society organizations (CSOs), academic institutions, and other research institutes as required. Through the provision of targeted technical assistance, BANTU will support the USAID Maternal Child Health (MCH), TB and HIV teams to conduct special studies and support USAID-led workshops with GOI. .The targeted technical expertise that BANTU provides contributes to the U.S. Mission efforts to elevate Indonesia's global and regional role promoting democratic values, rule of law, and protecting the environment, public health, and other shared priorities. Indonesia's progress across the various health sector concerns supports its long-term economic prosperity. The role of BANTU directly contributes to U.S. Government and Indonesian efforts to improve public health outcomes in MNH, TB and pandemic disease, which is aligned with the Journey to Self-Reliance Framework. The activity supports the Mission objective of Indonesia models good governance practices (manifested in public services, public policy, and legal/regulatory framework) to promote the development of a healthy, educated, and skilled population to drive inclusive economic growth. Accordingly, Indonesia increases responsiveness to the public by demonstrating accountability and consistently providing essential services...

Human Rights Activity

description.narrative: (Colombia): .Human rights abuses marked Colombia's five-decade conflict.and have continued at alarming rates since the signing of the 2016 Peace.Accord. Human rights defenders and social leaders, who play an essential.role in bringing just and sustainable peace to Colombia, are increasingly.targeted by criminal groups. Additionally, the COVID-19 pandemic has brought.new human rights challenges, as criminal groups increase social control in.already vulnerable communities... ..USAID/Colombia's Human Rights Activity (HRA) works to.advance a culture of civic rights, prevent human rights abuses, and provide.meaningful and effective responses to human rights violations. With FY.2020 funding, this activity will address the needs of groups, communities and.individuals disproportionately affected by human rights abuses, including.indigenous and Afro-Colombian communities; women and youth; migrants; LGBTI.persons; human rights defenders and social leaders; local journalists; and.conflict victims. HRA will provide technical assistance to the.Ombudsman's Early Warning System, Inter-Institutional Commission to Respond to.Early Alerts, National Protection Unit, Colombian National Police, and.sub-national governments to improve human rights protection, prevention, and.guarantees of non-repetition. HRA also will reduce stigmatization of.human rights defenders and social leaders and increase dialogue between.government and civil society actors. .. ..HRA contributes to the Integrated Country Strategy Mission.Goal of advancing Colombia's capacity to strengthen governance and transition.to a sustainable and inclusive peace. It helps Colombia on its Journey to.Self-Reliance by strengthening human rights protections, particularly for.vulnerable populations. ..

(Colombia): La actividad de los derechos humanos de USAID/Colombia (HRA) trabaja para avanzar una cultura de las derechas cívicas, prevenir abusos de derechos humanos, y proporciona respuestas significativas y eficaces a las violaciones de derechos humanos. Con la financiación 2018 del FY, esta actividad dirigirá las necesidades de los grupos afectados desproporcionado por violaciones de derechos humanos, incluyendo comunidades indígenas y Afro-colombianas; mujeres y juventud; Personas de LGBTI; defensores de los derechos humanos y líderes sociales; periodistas locales; y víctimas del conflicto. Dando prioridad a un acercamiento regional, HRA ayudará a contrapartes del gobierno a través de mecanismos de la asistencia técnica, tales como el sistema de alerta rápida del Defensor del Pueblo. HRA dirigirá riesgos y mejorará órdenes públicos con el desarrollo de capacidades de los oficiales del gobierno, de las campañas de la defensa del nivel nacional, y de los entrenamientos para reducir la estigmatización de los defensores de los derechos humanos y de los líderes sociales con los resultados previstos del diálogo creciente entre el gobierno y los actores de la sociedad civil, las medidas mejoradas de la protección para los defensores de los derechos humanos y los líderes sociales, y aumentó la visibilidad de las violaciones de derechos humanos. Esta actividad contribuye directamente al objetivo de misión de USG para ampliar la presencia eficaz de instituciones democráticas y de procesos en áreas apuntadas. La financiación 2018 del FY proporcionará $170.000 para el FY 2018 SFOAA-legisló reserva indígena Afro-colombiana de las comunidades.

Objectives for Colombia: USAID’s Human Rights Activity (HRA) works closely with GOC and civil society organizations in the seven conflict-affected regions of Antioquia, Córdoba, Tolima, Cauca, Nariño, Meta and Caquetá. The activity closely monitors the rapidly shifting regional dynamics impacting vulnerable populations and focuses efforts on those most in need. HRA is implemented by Chenomics and runs from April 2016 – April 2019.

title.narrative: Proyecto de la competitividad económica de USAID
USAID Economic Competitiveness Project

description.narrative: (El Salvador): Las ayudas del proyecto de la competitividad económica de USAID VAN y las instituciones del sector privado a aumentar la productividad y la competitividad de MSMEs en los sectores económicos dominantes. MSMEs es dominante a las posibilidades del crecimiento y del empleo del país, especialmente para la juventud vulnerable en área del delito grave. Con esta actividad, USAID fortalece procesos de producción de MSME, fomenta sociedades públicas-privado, y mejora el ambiente de negocio-permisión para animar la inversión, innovación, y las actividades financiadas de la creación de empleo. .FY 2018 incluyen asistencia técnica a los proveedores de servicios del desarrollo del público y de asunto privado, así ayudando a MSMEs a aumentar exportaciones, promover la innovación, aumentar la participación de las mujeres en negocio, y mejoran capacidad de suministro de servicios municipal. Los fondos también crearán las oportunidades para el mayor diálogo público-privado y ayudar a VA a aerodinamizar la política y regulaciones para mejorar el entorno empresarial. USAID trabajará a través de cadenas de valores para ligar a proveedores de MSME a los mercados de exportación. Además, los programas con las instituciones financieras en el país se han establecido para continuar trabajando en el acceso cada vez mayor a las finanzas para MSMEs. Esfuerzos también atraerán los fondos de inversión y a otras instituciones financieras del no-banco interesados en el ofrecimiento de productos del capital privado y de una oportunidad de invertir en MSMEs de crecimiento rápido potencial. Esto generará nuevos exportaciones y trabajos de aumentar las oportunidades económicas para salvadoreños, que ayudarán a provenir el flujo de migración irregular. Las iniciativas similares con otros proveedores de servicios locales del negocio, tales como la Cámara de Comercio, continuarán siendo ejecutadas para aumentar oportunidades económicas, para crear más trabajos y para reducir la migración ilegal. La actividad contribuye a la línea del "desarrollo de negocios" de acción debajo del pilar de la prosperidad del CEN. También contribuye al viaje a la métrica de la capacidad de la independencia del producto interno bruto (GDP) per capita y del entorno empresarial.... .... .

(El Salvador): Seventy-five percent of illegal migrants to the United States report economic reasons for emigrating. El Salvador's economy has been stagnant, averaging two percent GDP growth over the last 15 years. The COVID-19 pandemic has made the situation worse by contracting the economy and putting jobs at risk. This activity creates livelihoods and deters illegal migration by assisting the government and private sector institutions to increase micro, small, and medium-sized enterprises' (MSMEs) productivity and competitiveness in key economic sectors that are most likely to employ those with the most limited economic opportunities and likely to attempt to illegally migrate.The activity will assist El Salvador's economic recovery from COVID-19. FY 2020 funding will provide technical assistance to public and private business development service providers, help MSMEs increase exports and sales, increase business productivity, enhance women's participation in business, and improve government service delivery to MSMEs.Further, the activity will promote and facilitate high-quality U.S. investment opportunities to counter the potential investments of malign actors. It will assess the feasibility and risk of proposed Chinese investments while promoting and raising awareness of U.S. and other foreign direct investments. The activity will conduct an assessment of industries where this is most viable and provide technical assistance to our partners to realize those opportunities. The activity will stimulate private sector investments in support of America Crece by supporting the Development Finance Corporation's (DFC) pipeline of bankable deals and investment opportunities.... .... ..

title.narrative: Domestic Resource Mobilization
Movilización nacional del recurso

description.narrative: (El Salvador): Con la actividad nacional de la movilización del recurso (DRM), USAID apoya VA a continuar mejorando la eficacia y la transparencia de prácticas de gestión financieras públicas, y a generar los ingresos adicionales para las inversiones del sector público en los sectores críticos para la seguridad y el desarrollo de El Salvador tal como vigilancia, educación, y salud. La inversión en estos sectores permitirá que salvadoreños tengan acceso a mejores servicios públicos, mejorar sus condiciones de vida y, disuade en última instancia incentivos para emigrar. Esto incluye asistencia técnica al Ministerio de Finanzas (MOF) en las áreas de la política fiscal, la administración pública, los sistemas de gestión del gasto público y de los ingresos, así como ayuda para el diálogo público-privado entre el gobierno, el sector privado, y la sociedad civil. El DRM tiene cuatro componentes principales: Mejora del planeamiento y de la preparación del presupuesto; mejora de la ejecución del presupuesto; mejora de la política fiscal y de la administración; y, fortalecer la transparencia y diálogo público-privado en la política fiscal. .USAID utilizará fondos del FY 2018 para trabajar con el MOF en el estudio y la puesta en práctica de un marco fiscal y del gasto a medio plazo fuerte, que incluirá un pronóstico plurianual de ingresos y del gasto, y la micro-simulación de los escenarios del desarrollo fiscal y económico. El desarrollo de un sistema de gestión financiera integrado continuará para ligar transacciones financieras a través de las agencias de estatal de una manera más transparente y más eficaz. Además, USAID apoyará el fortalecimiento de la capacidad de MOF de conducir investigaciones del impuesto y dirige la evasión fiscal, especialmente para los contribuyentes grandes, que mejorarán recaudaciones de impuestos y opiniones del ciudadano de la eficacia y de la justicia del gobierno. .DRM apoya la línea del CEN de acción en la "mejora de gobierno" y también afecta directamente el viaje eficacia métrica de la capacidad de la independencia a la "de la administración fiscal. ".... .

(El Salvador): Through the Domestic Resource Mobilization (DRM) activity, USAID supports the GOES in enhancing public financial management practices, increasing domestic revenue mobilization and generating additional revenue for the public sector. USAID will use FY 2020 funds to support GOES financial management efforts as the country deals with loans and inflating expenses due to the COVID-19 outbreak. This activity will enhance transparency of COVID-19-related budgeting, anti-corruption and accountability efforts. It will also enable the maintenance of government funding and services to the most vulnerable segments of Salvadoran society that are likely to migrate. The activity provides technical assistance to the GOES Ministry of Finance (MOF) in tax policy, public administration, public expenditure and revenue management systems, and it works to increase dialogue between the government, the private sector, and civil society. It will facilitate technical assistance, training, direct IT support, and limited equipment support, to help the MOF implement a new financial management system. This will aid the GOES in developing a more efficient procurement process and reducing procurement costs.DRM will support both the Ministries of Health and Education in the implementation of a multi-year, results-oriented programmatic budget. Providing technical assistance, training and support from international advisors will allow management to make informed decisions on allocating scarce resources. DRM will also provide the MOF with recommendations tailored to mitigate negative economic and social impacts due to the COVID-19 pandemic and prevent an increase in tax evasion or avoidance..... .

description.narrative: (Guatemala): .USAID's Climate, Nature, and Communities in Guatemala (CNCG) promotes climate change mitigation by improving management of natural resources and biodiversity conservation, building capacity of key institutions, and strengthening policy and legal frameworks. Focused in the Western Highlands, Alta Verapaz and Baja Verapaz and the Maya Biosphere Reserve, CNCG will:.. .Develop and strengthen market-driven, community level conservation,Reduce vulnerability to climate change, andStrengthen non-governmental organizations.. ..CNCG will work with high-risk populations to weather current market and environmental shocks rather than migrating as a coping strategy. Quick impact interventions will conserve biodiversity along with maintaining and increasing forest cover in areas critical for small-scale agriculture and forest managers. Activities include establishment and expansion of existing native tree nurseries; creation and maintenance of short and medium-term jobs, and establishment of rapid partnerships with the private sector to support implementation and access to timber and non-timber markets... ..USAID will create market-driven job opportunities for underserved populations. It will help communities prepare for, mitigate, and address possible second-order economic, civilian-security, stabilization, and governance impacts of COVID-19. Interventions will enhance incomes for Guatemalan vulnerable populations who are now experiencing the economic shocks resulting from COVID-19. It will provide immediate response to reduce vulnerability and strengthen resilience by providing employment via natural-resource oriented small and medium enterprises. .. ..These activities support the Joint Strategic Plan Goal of "Renew America's Competitive Advantage for Sustained Economic Growth and Job Creation" by managing and conserving protected areas that harbor critical ecosystem services that play a key role in economic growth, fostering security, and good governance..

title.narrative: Communities Leading Development in Guatemala Project (CLD)
Comunidades que llevan el desarrollo en el proyecto de Guatemala (CLD)

description.narrative: (Guatemala): . .The Communities Leading Development (CLD) Project empowers citizens of the Western Highlands to identify and address their development needs. The project fosters inclusive participation of women, youth, and indigenous to identify and prioritize development needs in water, health, education, and economic growth. CLD communities are source communities for illegal migration to the United States. These communities face higher risks of exposure to COVID-19 given the high numbers of returned migrants present. Expanding access to services and building self-reliance in these communities will contribute to streaming illegal migration to the United States. The CLD project will support the following activities in FY 2020: a) Continue to empower families and communities through a local leadership training program and a menu of methodologies that build self-reliance and social cohesion. b) Leverage the private and public sectors to implement community prioritized development projects to improve community infrastructure, services, and expand economic opportunities. c) Expand access to financial resources, business services, fostering inclusive agricultural value chains, and training and equipping private service providers.. .Using the project's platform of community relationships and regular monitoring, CLD works with different entities in the GOG to connect the most vulnerable families with much needed GOG COVID-19 responses. CLD's will advise on priority needs, program quality, and provide logistics support, supervision, and monitoring as needed.. .CLD supports the Joint Strategic Plan (JSP) goal #2 "Renew America's competitive advantage for sustained economic growth and job creation." Specifically, activities directly support Strategic Objective 2.2 "Promote healthy, educated and productive populations in partner countries to drive inclusive and sustainable development, open new markets and support U.S. prosperity and security objectives"... .

(Guatemala):. El proyecto del CLD autorizará a ciudadanos de las montañas occidentales de Guatemala para identificar y dirigir su propio desarrollo necesita llegar a ser independiente y resistente. El proyecto fomentará la participación inclusiva de mujeres, de la juventud, y del trabajo con las comunidades para dar prioridad a los proyectos de desarrollo dominantes en agua, salud, la educación, y el desarrollo económico de mejorar su calidad de vida... . Los fondos de .FY 2018 apoyarán las actividades siguientes: 1. participación inclusiva de los miembros de la Comunidad en la identificación y necesidades y activos de la prioridad;. .2. El fortalecer de los consejos del desarrollo de comunidad para llevar el desarrollo y la supervisión de los planes de desarrollo de comunidad (CDPs);. .3. Compromiso de las organizaciones locales para ejecutar los proyectos responsivos a las prioridades del CDP;. .4. Priorización y diseño transparentes de proyectos responsivos a las prioridades del CDP;. .5. Movilización de contribuciones de comunidades, y sectores privados y de público para ejecutar proyectos;. .6. Servicios crecientes (e.g., servicios, salud, y educación del agua potable) y renta-generación de las actividades para los ciudadanos sanos, prósperos;. .7. Establecimiento del fondo de desarrollo de comunidad (CDF) para ampliar las maneras en las cuales los nuevos socios- del recurso privados y los sectores de público, las fundaciones, y guatemaltecos e internacionales donante-participan en el desarrollo de comunidad en las montañas occidentales; . .8. Compromiso a largo plazo y continuo creciente del sector privado en las montañas occidentales... . Las actividades de .CLD apuntan alentar independencia y resistencia con las inversiones en seguridad del agua, la salud, la educación, y el desarrollo económico que mejoran prosperidad y abren los nuevos mercados para la inversión de los E.E.U.U. Estas actividades apoyan la meta estratégica común #2 del plan, renovando la ventaja competitiva de América para el desarrollo económico y la creación de empleo continuos. Estas actividades apuntan directamente el área objetiva 2,2, por las poblaciones sanas, educadas y productivas el promover en Guatemala... .
